<body>
<header>
  <div style="margin-bottom:1rem"><a href="/">&larr; medicaldebtbankruptcy.com home</a></div>
  <h1>Medical Debt and Bankruptcy in Wyoming [2026]: Rules and Options</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">State-specific rules, federal bankruptcy filing data, and practical guidance for Wyoming residents.</p>
</header>
<div class="container">
<main>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Medical Debt in Wyoming: What You Need to Know</h2>
<p>Medical debt is the <em>leading cause of personal bankruptcy</em> in the United States. In Wyoming, the combination of federal consumer protections, state-specific laws, and hospital charity care programs determines how much leverage you have before filing becomes necessary.</p>
<p>Wyoming follows the federal CFPB framework for medical debt on credit reports. Under the federal rule, paid medical collections, medical debt under $500, and debt less than 12 months old cannot appear on consumer credit reports. No additional state-level protection applies in Wyoming.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Wyoming Medical Debt Rules</h2>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Protection</th><th>Wyoming Rule</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Credit Reporting</td><td>Follows federal CFPB rule.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Consumer Protection</td><td>No state-level medical debt credit reporting ban.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Hospital Liens</td><td>Hospital liens allowed.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Federal Protections That Apply in Wyoming</h2>
<p>Every Wyoming resident also benefits from these federal rules:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>No Surprises Act</strong> - bans most out-of-network surprise billing in emergency care and in-network facilities. See our <a href="/no-surprises-act.html">No Surprises Act guide</a>.</li>
  <li><strong>CFPB medical debt rule</strong> - medical collections under $500 and debt less than 12 months old excluded from credit reports; paid medical collections excluded.</li>
  <li><strong>Section 501(r)</strong> - nonprofit hospitals must have a written financial assistance policy and charge presumptively-eligible patients no more than amounts generally billed to insured patients.</li>
  <li><strong>Fair Debt Collection Practices Act</strong> - third-party medical collectors must follow notice and verification rules.</li>
</ul>
</div>



<div class="content-section">
<h2>Hospital Charity Care in Wyoming</h2>
<p>If your income is below the threshold set by Wyoming charity care rules (typically 200-400% of the federal poverty level), you may qualify for:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Free or steeply discounted hospital care for inpatient and emergency services.</li>
  <li>Retroactive application - charity care can sometimes be applied to bills already sent to collections.</li>
  <li>Waiver of interest and collection fees.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ask the hospital's billing office for the <em>financial assistance application</em> (501(r) for nonprofit hospitals). See <a href="/hospital-charity-care.html">our charity care guide</a> for the full process.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Bankruptcy as an Option in Wyoming</h2>
<p>When medical debt cannot be negotiated down or covered by charity care, bankruptcy is a legitimate tool:</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="/chapter-7-medical-debt.html">Chapter 7</a> wipes out medical debt in about 90 days. Unsecured medical bills are among the easiest debts to discharge.</li>
  <li><a href="/chapter-13-medical-debt.html">Chapter 13</a> pays a percentage of unsecured medical debt over 3-5 years and discharges the rest at plan completion.</li>
</ul>
<p>Use the <a href="https://bankruptcymeanstest.org/wyoming.html">Wyoming means test calculator</a> to check Chapter 7 eligibility, and the <a href="https://1328f.com">1328(f) screener</a> to check prior-case bars.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Medical Debt and Wyoming Bankruptcy Exemptions</h2>
<p>Bankruptcy does not mean losing your property - Wyoming exemptions protect most household goods, a vehicle, retirement accounts, and (usually) your home. See <a href="https://bankruptcyexemptionsbystate.com/states/wyoming.html">Wyoming exemptions</a> for the full list.</p>
<p>Medical debt is unsecured (no collateral), so the medical collector has no claim against your exempt property. Filing bankruptcy on medical debt is one of the cleanest fact patterns in consumer bankruptcy.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Related Wyoming Resources</h2>
<ul>
